00:20:23.643 --> 00:20:25.060 align:middle line:84%
This was the final
big change that

00:20:25.060 --> 00:20:27.490 align:middle line:84%
occurred in bread in the
last couple of generations.

00:20:27.490 --> 00:20:31.891 align:middle line:90%


00:20:31.891 --> 00:20:33.850 align:middle line:90%
>> This is my starter over here.

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:36.810 align:middle line:90%


00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:39.630 align:middle line:84%
Her name is baby cakes,
don't ask me why.

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:42.570 align:middle line:84%
I named all the other ones
after saints and things.

00:20:42.570 --> 00:20:47.560 align:middle line:84%
>> Up until World War II,
almost all bread was made

00:20:47.560 --> 00:20:49.990 align:middle line:84%
the old-fashioned way, which
is through fermentation.

00:20:49.990 --> 00:20:52.170 align:middle line:84%
It's through a
sourdough starter.

00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:54.460 align:middle line:84%
And sourdough starters,
despite all their mystique,

00:20:54.460 --> 00:20:55.310 align:middle line:90%
are very simple.

00:20:55.310 --> 00:20:58.710 align:middle line:84%
It's just you let flour
and water sit for days.

00:20:58.710 --> 00:21:01.630 align:middle line:84%
You've got to tend it a
little bit, refresh it,

00:21:01.630 --> 00:21:06.355 align:middle line:84%
and it becomes this
fermented kind of stinky goo.

00:21:06.355 --> 00:21:09.940 align:middle line:84%
>> This is what Chad and
French bakers are doing.

00:21:09.940 --> 00:21:11.890 align:middle line:84%
They use sourdough
starters which

00:21:11.890 --> 00:21:15.580 align:middle line:84%
collect bacteria and yeast
from the air around them.

00:21:15.580 --> 00:21:19.300 align:middle line:84%
And when mixed with dough,
